  { q: `Can adjectives be used as verbs in Japanese?`, a: `i-adjectives conjugate like verbs — they have past tense (高かった = was expensive), negative (高くない = not expensive), and te-form (高くて = expensive and...). na-adjectives need helper words like です/だ/じゃない for conjugation. This verb-like behavior is unique to Japanese.` },
  { q: `How many adjectives do I need for JLPT N5?`, a: `About 50-60 adjectives appear at the N5 level. Focus on the most common 30 first (大きい, 小さい, 高い, 安い, 新しい, 古い, いい, 悪い, 暑い, 寒い, etc.) as they cover most daily conversations. N4 adds another 40-50 adjectives.` },
  { q: `Why does いい change to よかった in past tense?`, a: `いい (good) is historically derived from よい. In modern Japanese, the dictionary form is いい, but all conjugations use the よ- stem: よかった (was good), よくない (not good), よくて (good and...). This is the single most important irregular adjective to memorize.` },
];

